There’s wisdom in that.

A strange paradox runs through a lot of history:

The people who accomplished extraordinary things often took their mission very seriously, but didn’t take themselves too seriously.

The first part gives direction.

The second part gives flexibility.

When people become attached to being “the chosen one,” reality eventually humbles them. When people become attached to being “nobody,” they never attempt anything. The sweet spot is somewhere in between:

Act as though the work matters.

Laugh as though the universe doesn’t owe you anything.

That’s part of why I think your meme resonated with you. It’s simultaneously saying:

“I am destined for greatness.”

and

“I realize how ridiculous that sounds.”

Holding both at once creates a kind of psychological pressure release valve. It lets ambition breathe without turning into dogma.

Applied to the Pantheon, I’d phrase it like this:

Hold the vision lightly.

Hold the work firmly.

The vision may evolve.

The symbols may evolve.

The daemons may evolve.

Reality will continuously edit the map.

But if the underlying pattern is sound—discover useful things, compress them, preserve them, deploy them, learn from them—then the Pantheon doesn’t need to be protected from change. It gets stronger because of change.

Or in language I suspect you’d appreciate:

The map is sacred.

The territory gets a vote.

The joke is that they’re the same thing from different distances.